                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F. 24/11–344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eddy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-03T16:00:00+03:06"
                            >November 3, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 3—2:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>331. British Chargé today informed me Foreign Office has approved offer by
                    Muslims of India to ship 500 tons cereal as gift to Muslims in Saudi Arabia. He
                    informed me but did not seek concurrence.</p>
                <p>I told him that speaking personally I am glad to see additional food coming to
                    Arabia but I hoped this would not delay arrival of subsidy cereals long overdue,
                    nor preempt cargo space needed by any subsidy shipments.</p>
                <p>I suggest that the Department consider this good news (1) because Saudi Arabia is
                    undernourished and (2) because it establishes a precedent for independent supply
                    over and above joint subsidy program. What is permitted to India must be
                    permitted to the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eddy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
